I was so shocked to encounter TSA in the US - I haven't met people as cold and rude in any other airport, and I actually visited the USSR before its fall. When you fly into the US, these horrible people are the first ones you meet - which sort of prepares you for contact with your almost equally unpleasant police, I guess, so it's a plus of sorts.

@Hardroch 

Hm, it's been 11 or 13 years, so I might have mixed up some things. Your comment made me question the details of my memories. I *do* remember some people treating us like cattle in US airports, shouting on repeat about fluids, gels and aerosols, glaring at us. It may have been during a transfer in Miami on our way to Jamaica - for some reason I think we had to go through immigration for that, which may explain mixing up arrivals and departures.

I also had one close encounter with American police once, in Arizona, and I felt genuinely threatened - mostly because the cop did in fact threaten me, with jail no less. What for? My rental's cheap tires screeching in a tight turn on a motel car park...

@Vaer 

This August I actually visited the castle that inspired Elsinore - Kronborg in Helsingør, Denmark - but not because of its Shakespearean connection: as became quite apparent today, I know very little about Hamlet (his name and Ophelia's, and not much else). I read the play almost 30 years ago and I'm not a theatre goer, either.

The castle is a UNESCO site, one of the best examples of a Renaissance residence and fortress in Northern Europe: I've always had a thing for architecture and history. Over the years I've visited most of Europe's major castles. As a boy I actually had it on my bucket list to see them all 🤩

